[1mNAME[0m[m
       gcc - GNU project C and C++ compiler[m
[m
[1mSYNOPSIS[0m[m
       gcc [[1m-c[0m|[1m-S[0m|[1m-E[0m] [[1m-std=[0m[4mstandard[24m][m
           [[1m-g[0m] [[1m-pg[0m] [[1m-O[0m[4mlevel[24m][m
           [[1m-W[0m[4mwarn[24m...] [[1m-Wpedantic[0m][m
           [[1m-I[0m[4mdir[24m...] [[1m-L[0m[4mdir[24m...][m
           [[1m-D[0m[4mmacro[24m[=[4mdefn[24m]...] [[1m-U[0m[4mmacro[24m][m
           [[1m-f[0m[4moption[24m...] [[1m-m[0m[4mmachine-option[24m...][m
           [[1m-o[0m [4moutfile[24m] [@[4mfile[24m] [4minfile[24m...[m
[m
       Only the most useful options are listed here; see below for the remainder.  [1mg++[0m accepts mostly the same options as [1mgcc[0m.[m
[m
[1mDESCRIPTION[0m[m
       When you invoke GCC, it normally does preprocessing, compilation, assembly and linking.  The "overall options" allow you[m
       to stop this process at an intermediate stage.  For example, the [1m-c[0m option says not to run the linker.  Then the output[m
       consists of object files output by the assembler.[m
[m
       Other options are passed on to one or more stages of processing.  Some options control the preprocessor and others the[m
       compiler itself.  Yet other options control the assembler and linker; most of these are not documented here, since you[m
       rarely need to use any of them.[m
[m
       Most of the command-line options that you can use with GCC are useful for C programs; when an option is only useful with[m
       another language (usually C++), the explanation says so explicitly.  If the description for a particular option does not[m
       mention a source language, you can use that option with all supported languages.[m
[m
       The usual way to run GCC is to run the executable called [1mgcc[0m, or [4mmachine[24m[1m-gcc[0m when cross-compiling, or [4mmachine[24m[1m-gcc-[0m[4mversion[24m[m
       to run a specific version of GCC.  When you compile C++ programs, you should invoke GCC as [1mg++[0m instead.[m
[m
       The [1mgcc[0m program accepts options and file names as operands.  Many options have multi-letter names; therefore multiple[m
       single-letter options may [4mnot[24m be grouped: [1m-dv[0m is very different from [1m-d[0m [1m-v[0m.[m
[m
       You can mix options and other arguments.  For the most part, the order you use doesn't matter.  Order does matter when[m
       you use several options of the same kind; for example, if you specify [1m-L[0m more than once, the directories are searched in[m
       the order specified.  Also, the placement of the [1m-l[0m option is significant.[m
